<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<configuration scan="true">

    <!-- Property Definitions -->
<property name="LOG_PATTERN" value="%d{yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.SSS} [%X{messageId}] %-5level %logger{36} - %msg%n" />
    <property name="LOG_FILE" value="logs/app.log" />

    <!-- Console Appender -->
    <appender name="Console" class="ch.qos.logback.core.ConsoleAppender">
        <encoder>
            <pattern>${LOG_PATTERN}</pattern>
        </encoder>
    </appender>

    <!-- File Appender (rotates daily) -->
    <appender name="RollingFile" class="ch.qos.logback.core.rolling.RollingFileAppender">
        <file>${LOG_FILE}</file>
        <rollingPolicy class="ch.qos.logback.core.rolling.TimeBasedRollingPolicy">
            <fileNamePattern>logs/app-%d{yyyy-MM-dd}.log</fileNamePattern>
            <maxHistory>30</maxHistory>
        </rollingPolicy>
        <encoder>
            <pattern>${LOG_PATTERN}</pattern>
        </encoder>
    </appender>

    <!-- Optional: JSON Appender (for ELK/EFK stacks) -->
    <!--
    <appender name="JsonConsole" class="ch.qos.logback.core.ConsoleAppender">
        <encoder class="net.logstash.logback.encoder.LogstashEncoder"/>
    </appender>
    -->

    <!-- Root Logger -->
    <root level="INFO">
        <appender-ref ref="Console" />
        <appender-ref ref="RollingFile" />
        <!-- <appender-ref ref="JsonConsole" /> -->
    </root>

    <!-- Logger for application classes -->
    <logger name="com.example.streambridge" level="DEBUG" additivity="false">
        <appender-ref ref="Console" />
        <appender-ref ref="RollingFile" />
    </logger>

</configuration>



### **1. Background**

The application currently runs on IBM WebSphere on a RHEL platform that has reached end-of-life. Two risk records were raised last year: one to address the **platform end-of-life**, and another to cover **critical vulnerabilities** identified in the RHEL/WebSphere servers. Both risks were placed under a **remediation path**, which involved moving the application to a newer RHEL environment with a WebSphere clustered topology. UAT for the new environment was completed; however, production cutover could not be executed within the approved window.

In parallel, the vendor released application version 18.x, which no longer supports WebSphere and requires a Spring Boot–based runtime. This change necessitates a new remediation path aligned with vendor-supported architecture.

---

### **2. Reason for Delay**

The remediation was delayed due to multiple factors:

* Overlapping mandatory upgrades, including the application version upgrade, Oracle upgrade, and SWIFT upgrade, which required the current production environment to remain operational.
* The vendor move to Spring Boot rendered the original WebSphere-based remediation path obsolete.
* Although the new RHEL environment was provisioned and UAT-approved, the **production cutover could not be executed due to the lack of an appropriate production window**.

---

### **3. Progress Made So Far**

Despite the delays, significant progress has been achieved:

* New RHEL environments were provisioned and **UAT for the application was signed off**.
* Production servers were built but the **cutover could not be executed due to lack of an appropriate window**.
* The signed-off version is now **outdated**, so the remediation path must ensure the application version on the current RHEL aligns with the version to be deployed on the new RHEL environment.
* Running parallel efforts on the current production environment and the new RHEL environment is **not feasible** due to business constraints; the cutover will be a **single, controlled deployment**.
* Application, Oracle, and SWIFT upgrades have been completed.
* Initial DR/BCP and integration readiness assessments have been completed.
* High-level remediation options have been identified, including **SAS-managed** and **in-house** deployment approaches.
* Risk exposure has been minimized through ongoing patching, monitoring, and controlled use of existing production servers.

---

